  "response": "To calculate CO2 emissions of a city, you'll need to consider several key sectors:\n\n1. Transportation Emissions\n- Vehicle miles traveled\n- Types of vehicles\n- Fuel consumption\n- Public transit usage\n\n2. Residential Sector\n- Total energy consumption\n- Electricity usage\n- Heating and cooling systems\n- Type of energy sources (gas, electricity, etc.)\n\n3. Commercial and Industrial Sector\n- Energy consumption\n- Industrial processes\n- Type of fuel used\n- Manufacturing activities\n\n4. Waste Management\n- Waste generation\n- Landfill methane emissions\n- Waste treatment methods\n\nCalculation Methods:\n- Use emission factors for different energy sources\n- Apply greenhouse gas protocol guidelines\n- Multiply energy consumption by specific CO2 emission coefficients\n- Use carbon calculators or specialized software\n\nData Sources:\n- Local utility companies\n- Municipal energy reports\n- National greenhouse gas inventories\n- Transportation departments\n- Statistical databases\n\nRecommended Tools:\n- ICLEI Global Protocol for Community-Scale Greenhouse Gas Emission Inventories\n- EPA's Center for Corporate Climate Leadership\n- Greenhouse Gas Protocol\n- City-specific carbon calculation tools\n\nFor precise calculations, consider consulting environmental experts or specialized carbon accounting professionals.",
